Chapter 4: Formal Model of the AES Agent

4.1 Agent State
Let an agent $a$ be associated with a state $s \in S$ where

$S = \mathcal{I} \times \mathcal{M} \times \mathcal{L} \times \mathcal{P}_{\text{fin}}(Goals) \times \mathcal{P}_{\text{fin}}(Constraints) \times \mathcal{H}$.

· $\mathcal{I}$ is the set of possible sensory inputs. We assume $\mathcal{I}$ is a finite set (e.g., a bounded vocabulary of sensor readings).
· $\mathcal{M}$ is the set of possible internal memory states. For finite‑state agents, $\mathcal{M}$ is finite; for infinite‑state agents (e.g., LLM context windows), we assume $\mathcal{M}$ is countable but we will use predicate abstraction to obtain a finite quotient.
· $\mathcal{L}$ is the set of possible knowledge bases. In practice, $\mathcal{L}$ is a set of finite sequences from a vocabulary; we assume it is countable and that we can define a finite set of predicates over it.
· $\mathcal{P}_{\text{fin}}(Goals)$ and $\mathcal{P}_{\text{fin}}(Constraints)$ are finite sets of goals and constraints.
· $\mathcal{H}$ is a finite lattice of health states (Chapter 7).

Because $\mathcal{L}$ can be arbitrarily large, $S$ is infinite. To enable finite‑state verification, we use predicate abstraction (Section 4.3) which reduces the state space to a finite quotient under a finite set of predicates.

4.2 Lifecycle as a Transition System
The agent’s execution proceeds through five phases, forming a loop that interacts with the environment:

1. perceive – read environment inputs (including messages from other agents) and produce observations.
2. update – incorporate observations into memory and knowledge.
3. plan – generate a plan from current goals and knowledge.
4. act – execute the first action of the plan, affecting the environment.
5. learn – update knowledge based on outcomes.

For deterministic agents, the transitions are functions. For stochastic agents (LLM‑based), each phase may induce a distribution over next states; we model this as an MDP.

To reason about the lifecycle we specify the effect of each phase on the atomic propositions (Table 4.1). The environment is modeled as an LTS that produces $p_{\text{in}}$ events; fairness (Definition 4.1) is an assumption about that environment—it guarantees that whenever an input is provided, resources will eventually be available for processing it.

