4.3 Predicate Abstraction
Let $\Pi = \{\pi_1, \dots, \pi_m\}$ be a finite set of predicates over $S$ such that for each $p \in AP$ there exists $\pi_p \in \Pi$ with $s \models p \iff \pi_p(s)$. Define $\alpha(s) = \{\pi \in \Pi \mid \pi(s)\}$ and $\gamma(\bar{s}) = \{ s \mid \alpha(s) \subseteq \bar{s} \}$.

The abstract transition system $\overline{T}_a$ has states $\overline{S} = 2^\Pi$ and transitions $\bar{s} \xrightarrow{\alpha} \bar{s}'$ if there exist $s \in \gamma(\bar{s})$, $s' \in \gamma(\bar{s}')$ with $s \xrightarrow{\alpha} s'$.

Theorem 4.1 (Soundness of Abstraction). If every run of $\overline{T}_a$ satisfies an LTL formula $\varphi$ over $AP$, then every run of $T_a$ satisfies $\varphi$.

Proof. Let $\rho = s_0 s_1 s_2\dots$ be a concrete run of $T_a$. Construct the abstract run $\overline{\rho} = \alpha(s_0)\alpha(s_1)\alpha(s_2)\dots$. By definition of the abstract transition relation, for each transition $s_i \to s_{i+1}$ in $T_a$ we have $\alpha(s_i) \to \alpha(s_{i+1})$ in $\overline{T}_a$. Moreover, because $\Pi$ contains predicates for each atomic proposition, the labeling of $\alpha(s_i)$ with $AP$ is identical to that of $s_i$. Therefore, $\rho \models \varphi$ iff $\overline{\rho} \models \varphi$. If $\rho$ violated $\varphi$, then $\overline{\rho}$ would also violate $\varphi$. Hence, if all abstract runs satisfy $\varphi$, no concrete run can violate it. ∎

Note. The converse does not hold: an abstract run may have no corresponding concrete run (spurious counterexample). This is addressed by the CEGAR refinement in Chapter 5.

4.4 LTL Specifications for Deterministic Compliance
We define three certification levels, each with distinct deadline $k$ and recovery bound $r$:

· Bronze: $k_{\text{Bronze}}$, $r_{\text{Bronze}}$
· Silver: $k_{\text{Silver}}$, $r_{\text{Silver}}$
· Gold: $k_{\text{Gold}}$, $r_{\text{Gold}}$

with $k_{\text{Gold}} < k_{\text{Silver}} < k_{\text{Bronze}}$ and $r_{\text{Gold}} < r_{\text{Silver}} < r_{\text{Bronze}}$.

Definition 4.1 (Fairness Assumption). An execution trace satisfies the fairness assumption $\mathsf{Fair}$ if it obeys $\mathsf{G}(p_{\text{in}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F} p_{\text{res}})$.

Definition 4.2 (Bronze Compliance). We define the four component formulas for Bronze. Their conjunction is denoted $\varphi^{\text{Bronze}}$.

1. Liveness:
      $\varphi_{\text{live}}^{\text{Bronze}} \equiv \mathsf{G}\bigl( p_{\text{in}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F}^{\le k_{\text{Bronze}}}( p_{\text{obs}} \land \mathsf{F}^{\le k_{\text{Bronze}}}( p_{\text{plan}} \land \mathsf{F}^{\le k_{\text{Bronze}}}( p_{\text{act}} \land \mathsf{F}^{\le k_{\text{Bronze}}} p_{\text{learn}} ) ) ) \bigr)$
2. Safety:
      $\varphi_{\text{safe}}^{\text{Bronze}} \equiv \mathsf{G}\bigl( p_{\text{error}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F}^{\le r_{\text{Bronze}}} \neg p_{\text{error}} \bigr)$
3. Progress:
      $\varphi_{\text{prog}}^{\text{Bronze}} \equiv \mathsf{G}\bigl( p_{\text{goals}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F}^{\le k_{\text{Bronze}}} p_{\text{plan}} \bigr)$
4. Deadlock freedom:
      $\varphi_{\text{dead}} \equiv \mathsf{G}\bigl( p_{\text{plan}} \rightarrow ( p_{\text{plan}} \mathsf{U} ( p_{\text{act}} \lor p_{\text{learn}} ) ) \bigr)$

The formulas for Silver and Gold are obtained by replacing $k_{\text{Bronze}}$ with $k_{\text{Silver}}$/$k_{\text{Gold}}$ and $r_{\text{Bronze}}$ with $r_{\text{Silver}}$/$r_{\text{Gold}}$ respectively. Their conjunctions are denoted $\varphi^{\text{Silver}}$ and $\varphi^{\text{Gold}}$.

Theorem 4.2 (Hierarchy). $\varphi^{\text{Gold}} \implies \varphi^{\text{Silver}} \implies \varphi^{\text{Bronze}}$.

Proof. Because $k_{\text{Gold}} < k_{\text{Silver}} < k_{\text{Bronze}}$ and $r_{\text{Gold}} < r_{\text{Silver}} < r_{\text{Bronze}}$, any trace satisfying a bounded temporal property with a tighter bound also satisfies it with a looser bound. The safety, progress, and deadlock formulas are identical except for the recovery bound in safety, which is also monotonic. Hence the implications hold. ∎

Remark. The deadlock formula $\varphi_{\text{dead}}$ is a monitoring target: it can be violated if the environment never provides $p_{\text{res}}$ after a plan is generated, causing the agent to wait indefinitely. Under the fairness assumption ($\mathsf{G}(p_{\text{in}}\to\mathsf{F}p_{\text{res}})$), the environment guarantees eventual resources, so the deadlock condition reduces to an agent‑internal obligation (Lemma 4.1).

4.5 Lifecycle Invariant for Deadlock Freedom

Lemma 4.1 (Plan Persistence). In a phase‑ordered AES agent, once $p_{\text{plan}}$ is raised, it remains true until either $p_{\text{act}}$ or $p_{\text{learn}}$ is raised. Formally, for any execution, whenever $p_{\text{plan}}$ holds at some step $i$, there exists a later step $j \ge i$ such that $p_{\text{act}} \lor p_{\text{learn}}$ holds at step $j$, and for all steps $i \le t < j$, $p_{\text{plan}}$ holds at step $t$.

Proof. From Table 4.1, only the act and learn phases clear $p_{\text{plan}}$. The plan phase raises it; perceive and update preserve it. Therefore, until an act or learn occurs, $p_{\text{plan}}$ remains true. ∎

With this lemma, $\varphi_{\text{dead}}$ is equivalent to the simpler condition $\mathsf{G}(p_{\text{plan}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F}(p_{\text{act}} \lor p_{\text{learn}}))$ (no plan stays forever), because persistence is guaranteed by the lifecycle. We will use this equivalence in the monitor (Chapter 8).

4.6 Parameter Selection and Domain Instantiation
The deadline and recovery bound parameters must be derived from the agent’s timing requirements. For a given agent, we compute worst‑case execution times (WCET) for each phase. Let $\text{WCET}_{\text{phase}}$ be the maximum duration of a phase (perceive, update, plan, act, learn). The monitor’s step granularity $\Delta t$ is the period at which it checks atomic propositions. For the liveness formula, each phase must complete within $k$ steps. Therefore we set $k_{\text{Gold}} = \lceil \max_{\text{phase}} \text{WCET}_{\text{phase}} / \Delta t \rceil$ so that the longest single phase can finish within $k_{\text{Gold}}$ steps. $k_{\text{Silver}}$ and $k_{\text{Bronze}}$ are set as multiples $m_{\text{Silver}} \cdot k_{\text{Gold}}$, $m_{\text{Bronze}} \cdot k_{\text{Gold}}$ with $m_{\text{Silver}} > 1$, $m_{\text{Bronze}} > m_{\text{Silver}}$. Recovery bounds $r$ are derived similarly from the WCET of the fault handling routine.

