Chapter 7: Lattice‑Based Graceful Degradation

7.1 Health Lattice
Let $\mathcal{H}$ be a finite chain: nominal $\succ$ degraded $\succ$ critical $\succ$ failure, with the partial order meaning “healthier than”. For each health state we have a corresponding atomic proposition $p_h$.

7.2 Diagnostic Predicates
The monitor evaluates predicates on sensor data to determine the current health. The mapping is as in Table 7.1.

Table 7.1: Health states and constraints

Sensor/Actuator Event Diagnostic Predicate Health State AES Level Operational Constraint
Nominal operation SNR > 20 dB ∧ Lat < 10 ms nominal Gold Unrestricted swarm ops
Event camera drift Var($f_{\text{events}}$) > $\theta_{\text{drift}}$ degraded Silver Max velocity ≤ 50 %
LiDAR occlusion $\sum$ Points < threshold critical Bronze E‑stop enabled / human‑in‑loop
Motor stall / IMU loss $I_{\text{motor}} > I_{\text{max}}$ ∨ no heartbeat failure None Immediate safe state

7.3 Monotone Certification
Define $\mathsf{certify}: \mathcal{H} \to \{\text{Gold},\text{Silver},\text{Bronze},\text{None}\}$ by $\mathsf{certify}(\text{nominal})=\text{Gold}$, $\mathsf{certify}(\text{degraded})=\text{Silver}$, $\mathsf{certify}(\text{critical})=\text{Bronze}$, $\mathsf{certify}(\text{failure})=\text{None}$. This function is monotone non‑increasing.

7.4 Behavior‑Monotonicity Assumption
We assume the health lattice is behavior‑monotone: if $h' \preceq h$ (i.e., $h'$ is less healthy), then the set of possible traces of the agent in state $h'$ is a subset of its traces in state $h$. This captures the intuition that degradation only removes capabilities, never adds new ones. For finite‑state agents, this can be enforced by construction: the degraded agent is obtained by disabling certain actions or narrowing the transition relation. For LLM agents, this assumption may not hold; we restrict the scope of the theorem to agents that satisfy this property, e.g., by design.

Theorem 7.1 (Safety under Degradation). Under the behavior‑monotonicity assumption, if an agent satisfies the AES compliance formulas for health state $h$ (at certification level $\mathsf{certify}(h)$), and its health degrades to $h' \preceq h$, then the agent remains compliant at the level $\mathsf{certify}(h')$ (with the corresponding LTL formulas).

Proof. By monotonicity of $\mathsf{certify}$, $\mathsf{certify}(h') \le \mathsf{certify}(h)$. The LTL formulas for lower levels are either identical or weaker (e.g., larger deadlines). By behavior‑monotonicity, all traces in health $h'$ are also traces in health $h$. Since the agent satisfied the formulas for $h$, it must also satisfy the (weaker) formulas for $h'$. ∎

7.5 Lean 4 Formalization
We formalize the health lattice and monotonicity in Lean 4. The following type signature states the theorem:

```lean
theorem safety_monotone (h h' : Health) (h'_le_h : h' ≺ h)
  (cert : Health → CertLevel) (mono_cert : cert h' ≤ cert h)
  (beh_mono : traces h' ⊆ traces h)
  (compliant : ∀ tr ∈ traces h, tr ⊧ φ (cert h)) :
  ∀ tr ∈ traces h', tr ⊧ φ (cert h')
```

The full proof is available in the accompanying technical report.

