Chapter 8: Runtime Monitor Construction – Deterministic Case

8.1 Monitor for $\varphi_{\text{live}}$ with Fairness
The monitor maintains a queue of timers, each a 4‑tuple $(o,p,a,l)$ initialized to $(k,k,k,k)$ upon a new $p_{\text{in}}$. At each step, if $p_{\text{res}}$ is true, all active timers decrement their first non‑zero counter; otherwise they freeze. When a timer’s counter reaches zero while still active, the monitor outputs $\bot$ (violation). When a phase is completed, the corresponding counter is set to zero. When all counters of the front timer are zero, it is dequeued. If the queue becomes empty, the monitor outputs $\top$. Otherwise the verdict is pending.

8.2 Four‑Valued Semantics
Our monitor implements the 4‑valued semantics of runtime verification for LTL (Bauer, Leucker & Schallhart 2011, “Runtime Verification for LTL and TLTL”, ACM TOSEM). The verdicts $\top$ (true), $\bot$ (false), $\top_p$ (pending true), and $\bot_p$ (pending false) correspond to the standard RV‑LTL truth values. The monitor’s transition function is a deterministic automaton that outputs a verdict at each step based on the observed atomic propositions.

Theorem 8.1 (Monitor Correctness under Fairness). Let $\sigma$ be an infinite trace. Then:

· If the monitor outputs $\bot$ at position $i$, there exists a fairness‑satisfying extension of $\sigma[0..i]$ that violates $\varphi_{\text{live}}$.
· If the monitor outputs $\top$ at position $i$, every fairness‑satisfying extension satisfies $\varphi_{\text{live}}$.
· Otherwise, the verdict is $\top_p$ (pending satisfaction) or $\bot_p$ (pending violation) according to the 4‑valued semantics.

Proof. By induction on prefix length. The base case (empty prefix) gives pending satisfaction. For the inductive step, the monitor’s transition depends on the incoming propositions and the current queue. The key cases are: when a timer expires while $p_{\text{res}}$ holds, the deadline is permanently missed, so no fairness‑satisfying extension can satisfy $\varphi_{\text{live}}$; when the queue empties, all pending inputs have completed, so all extensions satisfy $\varphi_{\text{live}}$. The full proof is a standard product construction for bounded liveness extended with resource‑aware timer freezing. ∎

The following Lean 4 type signatures capture the two directions of the statement:

```lean
theorem monitor_bot_sound (σ : InfiniteTrace AP) (i : ℕ) :
  monitor_outputs_bot σ i → ∃ ext, fair ext ∧ ¬(σ.take i ++ ext ⊨ φ_live)

theorem monitor_top_sound (σ : InfiniteTrace AP) (i : ℕ) :
  monitor_outputs_top σ i → ∀ ext, fair ext → (σ.take i ++ ext ⊨ φ_live)
```

8.3 Monitoring Deadlock Freedom
Because $\varphi_{\text{dead}}$ is equivalent to $\mathsf{G}(p_{\text{plan}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F}(p_{\text{act}} \lor p_{\text{learn}}))$ by Lemma 4.1, we can monitor deadlock using a separate timer: when $p_{\text{plan}}$ is observed, we start a timer with a fixed bound $k_{\text{dead}}$ (which can be taken as the maximum allowed waiting time, possibly $k$ for the tier). If the timer expires before $p_{\text{act}} \lor p_{\text{learn}}$ occurs, a violation is reported. This is a standard bounded liveness monitor.

8.4 Monitor State Complexity
For $m$ overlapping inputs, the monitor has at most $((k+1)^4+2)^m$ states.

