Chapter 9: Blast Radius Formalization

9.1 Communication Graph
Let $G = (V, E)$ be a directed graph where $V$ is the set of agents, and $(a,b) \in E$ if agent $a$ sends input to agent $b$. We assume the graph is acyclic to simplify analysis (or we can consider the strongly connected components as single units). The certification level of an agent $a$ is $\mathsf{Cert}(a)$.

9.2 Failure Propagation Model
When an agent fails (i.e., violates its compliance guarantee), it may propagate erroneous inputs to its successors. We model propagation probability $\delta_{a \to b} \in [0,1]$ as the probability that a failure of $a$ causes $b$ to fail, given that $a$ fails. For Gold agents, we set $\delta_{a \to b} = 0$ for all $b$, because Gold agents are designed to contain failures (e.g., through refusal filters). For Silver and Bronze agents, propagation probabilities are bounded by the certification level.

9.3 Blast Radius Definition
The blast radius of a failure at agent $a$ is the expected number of agents that fail as a result, under the propagation model. Formally:

\text{BR}(a) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \sum_{v \in V} \mathbf{1}_{\text{$v$ fails}} \;\middle|\; a \text{ fails} \right].

Given the propagation graph and probabilities, the expected blast radius can be computed as the sum over all nodes of the probability that they are reachable from $a$ via a path where each edge’s propagation probability is multiplied.

9.4 Bounding Blast Radius with Certification
For a system where Gold agents have zero propagation probability, the expected blast radius of any agent can be bounded using the probabilities along paths.

Theorem 9.1 (Blast Radius Bound). If for every Gold agent $g$, $\delta_{g \to v} = 0$ for all $v$, then for any agent $a$,

\text{BR}(a) \le 1 + \sum_{v \neq a} \min\!\left(1,\ \sum_{\text{paths } p: a \leadsto v} \prod_{e \in p} \delta_e\right),

where the sum over paths includes all directed paths that do not pass through Gold agents (except possibly as endpoints). In particular, if the communication graph has no path from $a$ to any non‑Gold agent (e.g., all successors are Gold), then $\text{BR}(a) = 1$.

Proof. By linearity of expectation, $\text{BR}(a) = \sum_v \Pr[v \text{ fails} \mid a \text{ fails}]$. For a non‑Gold agent $v$, the only way it can fail is through a chain of propagations starting from $a$ and not passing through Gold agents (since Gold agents do not propagate). By the union bound over all such paths, the probability that $v$ fails is at most the sum over paths of the product of edge probabilities along the path. The min with 1 accounts for the fact that probability cannot exceed 1. For Gold agents, the failure probability is zero if they are not $a$ itself. Summing yields the bound. ∎

Remark. This is a sound upper bound. It is tight when paths are edge‑disjoint (no shared failure modes) and becomes conservative in graphs with multiple paths sharing edges. The exact blast radius can be computed using inclusion‑exclusion or network reliability algorithms (e.g., Provan–Ball for DAGs). For certification purposes, the union bound provides a safe over‑approximation.

