Chapter 10: Compositional Verification with Trust

10.1 Trust‑Weighted Contracts
We assume an acyclic dependency graph among agents (as in Chapter 9). Each agent $a$ has a certification level $\mathsf{Cert}(a)$. A Gold agent trusts inputs from Silver or higher; a Silver agent trusts Bronze or higher; a Bronze agent trusts only certified agents; a None agent is not trusted by anyone.

10.2 Resource‑Fairness Assumption for Composition
To ensure that fairness ($\mathsf{G}(p_{\text{in}} \rightarrow \mathsf{F} p_{\text{res}})$) holds in the composed system, we must bound the incoming message rate. We formalize this using a metric temporal logic (MTL) formula. Let $\text{rate}_{[t,t+w]}(p_{\text{in}})$ denote the number of $p_{\text{in}}$ events in the interval $[t,t+w]$. For each agent $a$, we assume the environment satisfies:

\mathsf{Fair}_{\text{res}}(R_a, w, d) \equiv \mathsf{G}\Bigl( \bigl( \text{rate}_{[t,t+w]}(p_{\text{in}}) \le R_a \cdot w \bigr) \rightarrow \mathsf{F}^{\le d} p_{\text{res}} \Bigr)

for given parameters $R_a$, $w$, $d$. This says that as long as the input rate does not exceed $R_a$ (in any window of length $w$), resources will become available within $d$ steps.

10.3 Refusal Primitive with Rate Limiting
A Gold agent is equipped with a function $\text{Refuse}: \text{Msg} \times \mathsf{CertLevel} \times \text{rate\_history} \to \{\text{pass},\text{drop}\}$. For every incoming message, regardless of certification level, the agent checks two conditions:

· Safety: if the sender's certification level is below Gold, $\psi_{\text{safe}}(\text{sender})$ must hold (a safety envelope). For higher‑certification senders, safety is assumed by trust.
· Rate: the current rate of messages from the sender (computed over a sliding window) must not exceed a per‑sender budget $B_a(sender)$. The budget may be larger for higher‑certification senders, but it is finite.

If either condition fails, the message is dropped and does not trigger $p_{\text{in}}$. This ensures that the effective environment seen by the agent satisfies both safety and the rate condition of $\mathsf{Fair}_{\text{res}}$ for all incoming messages, because the per‑sender budgets are chosen so that the sum over all senders is at most $R_a$.

10.4 Composition Theorem
For each agent $a$, let $A_a$ be an LTL formula over the propositions of its peers that formalizes the assumption that inputs from trusted peers are safe and that the input rate is bounded as in Section 10.2. Let $G_a$ be the AES compliance formula appropriate to $\mathsf{Cert}(a)$ (including the resource‑fairness assumption). We require that the assume‑guarantee contract $\langle A_a \rangle\; a\; \langle G_a \rangle$ holds: for all environments $E$ whose observable behavior satisfies $A_a$, the execution of agent $a$ in $E$ produces traces satisfying $G_a$.

Theorem 10.1 (Trust‑Weighted Compositional Correctness). Under the acyclic ordering, if for every agent $a$ the contract $\langle A_a \rangle\; a\; \langle G_a \rangle$ holds, and Gold agents implement the refusal primitive with rate limiting as described, then the composition satisfies $\bigwedge_a G_a$, even in the presence of non‑certified agents.

Proof. By induction on the order. The base case (no inputs) is trivial. For the inductive step, consider agent $a$. Its assumptions $A_a$ refer only to lower‑order agents, which by induction satisfy their guarantees. The refusal primitive ensures that any message that would violate $A_a$ (either safety or rate) is dropped, so the actual inputs to $a$ satisfy $A_a$. The rate‑limiting part guarantees that the condition $\text{rate}_{[t,t+w]}(p_{\text{in}}) \le R_a \cdot w$ holds globally; hence $\mathsf{Fair}_{\text{res}}$ holds, and therefore $p_{\text{res}}$ occurs within $d$ steps after each $p_{\text{in}}$. The contract then gives that $a$ satisfies $G_a$. ∎

