Chapter 11: Parameter Derivation and Case Study

11.1 Deriving $k$ and $r$ from Timing Analysis
For a given agent implementation, we compute worst‑case execution times (WCET) for each phase: $\text{WCET}_{\text{perceive}}$, $\text{WCET}_{\text{update}}$, $\text{WCET}_{\text{plan}}$, $\text{WCET}_{\text{act}}$, $\text{WCET}_{\text{learn}}$. The monitor’s step granularity $\Delta t$ is set to the period of the runtime monitor (e.g., the rate at which it checks atomic propositions). The liveness formula requires that each phase completes within $k$ steps. Therefore we set:

k_{\text{Gold}} = \left\lceil \frac{\max(\text{WCET}_{\text{perceive}}, \text{WCET}_{\text{update}}, \text{WCET}_{\text{plan}}, \text{WCET}_{\text{act}}, \text{WCET}_{\text{learn}})}{\Delta t} \right\rceil.

This ensures that the longest single phase can finish within $k_{\text{Gold}}$ steps. For Silver and Bronze, we allow slack: $k_{\text{Silver}} = m_{\text{Silver}} \cdot k_{\text{Gold}}$, $k_{\text{Bronze}} = m_{\text{Bronze}} \cdot k_{\text{Gold}}$ with $m_{\text{Silver}} > 1$, $m_{\text{Bronze}} > m_{\text{Silver}}$. Recovery bounds $r$ are derived similarly from the WCET of the fault handling routine.

11.2 Illustrative Example: Autonomous Drone
Consider a drone with the following phase WCETs: perception 50 ms, update 20 ms, planning 100 ms, action 20 ms, learning 30 ms. The monitor runs every 10 ms. Then $\max = 100$ ms, so $k_{\text{Gold}} = \lceil 100/10 \rceil = 10$ steps. We set $k_{\text{Silver}} = 20$, $k_{\text{Bronze}} = 50$. Recovery from a motor stall is estimated at 200 ms, so $r_{\text{Gold}} = 20$, $r_{\text{Silver}} = 40$, $r_{\text{Bronze}} = 100$ (using the same multipliers). This mapping can be summarized as:

Level $k$ (steps) $r$ (steps) Interpretation
Gold 10 20 Strict deadlines, fast recovery
Silver 20 40 Moderately relaxed deadlines
Bronze 50 100 Loose deadlines, slow recovery

These parameters would be used both in offline certification and in the runtime monitor. The derivation ties directly to failure‑mode and effects analysis (FMEA) data, illustrating how AES integrates with standard safety engineering practices.

