Chapter 12: Architecture and Design

12.1 Overall System Architecture
The AES framework comprises three main components:

1. Offline Certification Toolchain – Performs static verification using predicate abstraction, CEGAR, and probabilistic model checking. It takes as input the agent’s source code (or a high‑level model) and produces a set of predicates $\Pi^*$ and a certified abstract model $\overline{T}_a$ that is LTL‑equivalent for the AES properties. It also outputs the certification level and the bounds $k$ and $r$ for the runtime monitor.
2. Runtime Monitor – Injects into the agent’s execution loop, observes atomic propositions, updates internal state (timer queue, health state), and emits verdicts (compliant, warning, violation). It uses the predicates $\Pi^*$ to evaluate atomic propositions efficiently.
3. Composition Manager – Coordinates multiple agents, checks trust levels, installs refusal filters as needed, and enforces resource‑fairness constraints. It also monitors the communication graph to bound blast radius.

12.2 Interfaces
The Offline Toolchain outputs a tuple $(\Pi^*, \overline{T}_a, \text{cert\_level}, k, r)$. The Runtime Monitor expects an interface to the agent that provides the values of the atomic propositions at each step, which must be consistent with $\Pi^*$ (i.e., the agent must expose the predicates in $\Pi^*$). We call this monitor‑compatibility.

Definition 12.1 (Monitor‑Compatibility). An agent $a$ is monitor‑compatible with a predicate set $\Pi$ if for every $s \in S_a$, the value of each $\pi \in \Pi$ can be observed at runtime (i.e., the agent provides a function that returns the truth of $\pi$ in the current state). Moreover, the runtime evaluation of the atomic propositions $AP$ must match the predicates $\pi_p$ used in the offline certification.

Remark. Monitor‑compatibility is a design‑time obligation—the agent must be instrumented to expose the predicates $\Pi^*$ via efficient runtime checks (e.g., logging hooks or shadow variables). This mirrors the “instrumentation for runtime verification” pattern in the RV‑LTL literature.

Theorem 12.1 (Soundness of Runtime Monitoring). If the offline certification produces $\Pi^*$ such that $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) \models \varphi$, and the concrete system $T_a$ at runtime is the same system that was certified offline (i.e., the agent’s behavior model has not changed since certification), and the agent is monitor‑compatible with $\Pi^*$, then the runtime monitor’s verdicts are sound: a $\bot$ verdict indicates a real violation of $\varphi$, and a $\top$ verdict indicates that $\varphi$ holds for all future extensions that satisfy fairness.

Proof. The offline certification guarantees that every concrete trace of $a$ satisfies $\varphi$ iff the abstract trace satisfies $\varphi$. The monitor’s verdicts are based on the abstract trace (via the observed predicates). Theorem 8.1 ensures that the monitor’s verdicts are correct for the abstract trace. By monitor‑compatibility, the abstract trace corresponds to the concrete trace, so the verdicts are correct for the concrete agent. ∎

Remark. For LLM‑based agents, the runtime behavior may drift from the certified model. In such cases, the monitor can still be used to detect divergence: if the sliding‑window violation rate exceeds the certified tolerance $\epsilon$ for a sustained period, the system should either degrade gracefully or trigger a re‑certification workflow. This is an extension of the probabilistic monitoring described in Chapter 6.

12.3 Refusal Filter Architecture
For Gold agents that need to interoperate with untrusted peers, a refusal filter is placed in front of the perception module. It validates each incoming message against safety and rate conditions as described in Section 10.3; if validation fails, the message is dropped and $p_{\text{in}}$ is not raised for that input. This ensures that the agent’s state update only processes trusted information. The filter is part of the runtime monitor’s extension for Gold agents.

The architecture separates the certification process into an offline verification stage that produces a certified abstract model, a runtime monitor that enforces compliance online, and a composition manager that orchestrates multi‑agent interactions. This modular design aligns with safety‑critical system standards (e.g., ISO 26262) and facilitates incremental certification.

