A.1 Proof of Theorem 4.1 (Soundness of Abstraction)

Theorem 4.1 (Soundness of Abstraction).
If every run of $\overline{T}_a$ satisfies an LTL formula $\varphi$ over $AP$, then every run of $T_a$ satisfies $\varphi$.

Proof.
Let $\rho = s_0 s_1 s_2 \dots$ be a concrete run of $T_a$. Define the abstract run $\overline{\rho} = \alpha(s_0)\alpha(s_1)\alpha(s_2)\dots$ where $\alpha(s) = \{\pi \in \Pi \mid \pi(s)\}$.

We first show that $\overline{\rho}$ is a valid run of $\overline{T}_a$. For each transition $s_i \xrightarrow{\ell} s_{i+1}$ in $T_a$, there exist $s \in \gamma(\alpha(s_i))$ and $s' \in \gamma(\alpha(s_{i+1}))$ such that $s \xrightarrow{\ell} s'$ (take $s = s_i$, $s' = s_{i+1}$). By definition of the abstract transition relation, $\alpha(s_i) \xrightarrow{\ell} \alpha(s_{i+1})$ in $\overline{T}_a$. Hence $\overline{\rho}$ is a valid run.

Because $\Pi$ contains predicates for each atomic proposition $p \in AP$, we have $s_i \models p \iff \pi_p(s_i) \iff \pi_p \in \alpha(s_i)$. Thus the labeling of $\alpha(s_i)$ with $AP$ is identical to that of $s_i$. Consequently, for any LTL formula $\varphi$ over $AP$, $\rho \models \varphi$ iff $\overline{\rho} \models \varphi$.

Now assume that every run of $\overline{T}_a$ satisfies $\varphi$. Then $\overline{\rho} \models \varphi$, so $\rho \models \varphi$. Since $\rho$ was arbitrary, every run of $T_a$ satisfies $\varphi$. ∎

---

A.2 Proof of Theorem 4.2 (Hierarchy)

Theorem 4.2 (Hierarchy). $\varphi^{\text{Gold}} \implies \varphi^{\text{Silver}} \implies \varphi^{\text{Bronze}}$.

Proof.
Recall that $\varphi^{\text{Gold}} = \varphi_{\text{live}}^{\text{Gold}} \land \varphi_{\text{safe}}^{\text{Gold}} \land \varphi_{\text{prog}}^{\text{Gold}} \land \varphi_{\text{dead}}$, and similarly for Silver and Bronze, with $k_{\text{Gold}} < k_{\text{Silver}} < k_{\text{Bronze}}$ and $r_{\text{Gold}} < r_{\text{Silver}} < r_{\text{Bronze}}$.

For any trace $\sigma$, if $\sigma \models \varphi_{\text{live}}^{\text{Gold}}$, then in particular, for every occurrence of $p_{\text{in}}$, the nested bounded liveness chain completes within $k_{\text{Gold}}$ steps per phase. Since $k_{\text{Gold}} < k_{\text{Silver}}$, the same chain also completes within $k_{\text{Silver}}$ steps, so $\sigma \models \varphi_{\text{live}}^{\text{Silver}}$. A similar argument holds for $\varphi_{\text{live}}^{\text{Silver}} \implies \varphi_{\text{live}}^{\text{Bronze}}$.

The safety formulas are $\mathsf{G}(p_{\text{error}} \to \mathsf{F}^{\le r} \neg p_{\text{error}})$. Since $r_{\text{Gold}} < r_{\text{Silver}} < r_{\text{Bronze}}$, satisfaction with a tighter bound implies satisfaction with a looser bound.

The progress formulas $\varphi_{\text{prog}}$ have the same monotonicity in $k$. The deadlock formula $\varphi_{\text{dead}}$ is identical in all three tiers. Therefore $\sigma \models \varphi^{\text{Gold}}$ implies $\sigma \models \varphi^{\text{Silver}}$, and similarly Silver implies Bronze. ∎

