A.3 Proof of Lemma 4.1 (Plan Persistence)

Lemma 4.1 (Plan Persistence).
In a phase‑ordered AES agent, once $p_{\text{plan}}$ is raised, it remains true until either $p_{\text{act}}$ or $p_{\text{learn}}$ is raised.

Proof.
From Table 4.1, the only phases that can clear $p_{\text{plan}}$ are act and learn. The plan phase raises $p_{\text{plan}}$; the perceive and update phases preserve it (they do not modify $p_{\text{plan}}$). Thus, after $p_{\text{plan}}$ becomes true, it stays true until an act or learn transition occurs. Formally, for any execution, if $p_{\text{plan}}$ holds at step $i$, define $j$ as the smallest index $j \ge i$ such that $p_{\text{act}} \lor p_{\text{learn}}$ holds at step $j$. By the phase ordering, no other phase can set $p_{\text{plan}}$ to false before $j$, so $p_{\text{plan}}$ holds for all $i \le t < j$. ∎

