A.4 Proof of Theorem 5.1 (CEGAR Soundness and Completeness)

Theorem 5.1 (CEGAR Soundness and Completeness).
For a finite‑state concrete system (or a system with a finite bisimulation quotient), the CEGAR loop terminates with a set of predicates $\Pi^*$ such that for every LTL property $\varphi$ over $AP$, $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) \models \varphi$ iff $T_a \models \varphi$.

Proof.
Let $T_a$ be a finite‑state LTS. The set of all states $S$ is finite, so there exists a finite bisimulation quotient $S/{\sim}$ (the set of equivalence classes of states indistinguishable by any LTL formula over $AP$). Predicate abstraction with a set of predicates $\Pi$ yields an abstract state space $2^\Pi$. The abstract system $\overline{T}_a(\Pi)$ is a finite LTS with at most $2^{|\Pi|}$ states.

The CEGAR loop starts with $\Pi_0 = \{\pi_p \mid p \in AP\}$. At each iteration, if $\overline{T}_a(\Pi_i) \models \varphi$, we are done. Otherwise, we obtain a counterexample $\overline{\rho}$. If it is concrete, we report a violation. If it is spurious, we compute a new predicate $\pi$ that eliminates it and set $\Pi_{i+1} = \Pi_i \cup \{\pi\}$.

Because $T_a$ has a finite bisimulation quotient, the number of distinct abstract states needed to distinguish all LTL properties is bounded by the size of the quotient. Each new predicate $\pi$ refines the abstraction, i.e., it splits at least one abstract state into two distinct states. Thus the number of refinements is at most $|2^{|\Pi_{\text{max}}|}|$, where $|\Pi_{\text{max}}|$ is the number of predicates required to exactly characterize the bisimulation quotient. Hence the loop terminates.

When it terminates, we have $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) \models \varphi$ and there is no spurious counterexample. For any concrete run $\rho$, its abstract trace $\overline{\rho}$ is a run in $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*)$. If $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) \models \varphi$, then $\overline{\rho} \models \varphi$, so $\rho \models \varphi$ by soundness. Conversely, if there were a concrete run violating $\varphi$, its abstract trace would be a counterexample in the abstraction, contradicting the termination condition. Hence $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) \models \varphi$ iff $T_a \models \varphi$. ∎

