A.7 Proof of Theorem 8.1 (Monitor Correctness under Fairness)

Theorem 8.1 (Monitor Correctness under Fairness).
Let $\sigma$ be an infinite trace. Then:

· If the monitor outputs $\bot$ at position $i$, there exists a fairness‑satisfying extension of $\sigma[0..i]$ that violates $\varphi_{\text{live}}$.
· If the monitor outputs $\top$ at position $i$, every fairness‑satisfying extension satisfies $\varphi_{\text{live}}$.

Proof.
We define the monitor as a deterministic automaton $\mathcal{M}$ with states $(q, T)$ where $q \in \{\top,\bot,\top_p,\bot_p\}$ and $T$ is a queue of timers. The transition function depends on the observed atomic propositions at each step. The correctness proof follows the standard RV‑LTL approach (Bauer et al. 2011) adapted for bounded liveness with resource freezing.

We prove by induction on the length $i$ of the observed prefix $\sigma[0..i]$. Let $v_i$ be the monitor verdict after processing $i$ steps.

Base case ($i=0$). The monitor has no input; its state is $(\top_p, \text{empty})$, so it outputs $\top_p$. The statement holds vacuously because there is no $\bot$ or $\top$ output.

Inductive step. Assume the claim holds for all prefixes of length $i$. Consider prefix $\sigma[0..i+1]$.

Case 1: $v_{i+1} = \bot$.
The monitor outputs $\bot$ only when a timer expires while $p_{\text{res}}$ holds. Let the expired timer be for an input that occurred at time $t \le i+1$. The timer expiration means that the required phase (observe, plan, act, or learn) did not occur within $k$ steps after the previous phase completed, despite resources being available. Because $p_{\text{res}}$ held at the expiration step, the fairness assumption cannot make $p_{\text{res}}$ hold again later to remedy the missed deadline—once a deadline is missed, it cannot be retroactively satisfied. Therefore, any extension $\rho$ of $\sigma[0..i+1]$ that satisfies fairness still has the same missed deadline, so $\rho \not\models \varphi_{\text{live}}$. The existence of such an extension is trivial (any infinite extension works). Hence the condition holds.

Case 2: $v_{i+1} = \top$.
The monitor outputs $\top$ only when the timer queue becomes empty. This means that all inputs that occurred up to $i+1$ have been fully processed (all phases completed) and no input is pending. In any extension $\rho$ that satisfies fairness, any future input will be processed according to the same bounded deadlines. Since the queue is empty, there is no pending obligation; thus $\rho \models \varphi_{\text{live}}$. This holds for all extensions.

Case 3: $v_{i+1} = \top_p$ or $\bot_p$.
By induction, the verdict after $i$ steps was $\top_p$ or $\bot_p$ and the monitor state is consistent with the RV‑LTL semantics. The transition to $\top_p$ or $\bot_p$ means that no definitive verdict has been reached; the monitor will continue to monitor. The claim for these pending verdicts is that the eventual verdict (when a final $\top$ or $\bot$ is issued) will satisfy the conditions, which follows from the inductive hypothesis. ∎

