A.8 Proof of Theorem 9.1 (Blast Radius Bound)

Theorem 9.1 (Blast Radius Bound).
If for every Gold agent $g$, $\delta_{g \to v} = 0$ for all $v$, then for any agent $a$,

\text{BR}(a) \le 1 + \sum_{v \neq a} \min\!\left(1,\ \sum_{\text{paths } p: a \leadsto v} \prod_{e \in p} \delta_e\right),

where the sum over paths includes all directed paths that do not pass through Gold agents (except possibly as endpoints).

Proof.
Let $F_v$ be the indicator that agent $v$ fails, given that $a$ fails. Then $\text{BR}(a) = \sum_v \mathbb{E}[F_v] = \sum_v \Pr[v \text{ fails} \mid a \text{ fails}]$.

For $v = a$, $\Pr[a \text{ fails} \mid a \text{ fails}] = 1$.

For $v \neq a$, consider the propagation graph. A failure of $v$ can only occur if there is a chain of propagations from $a$ to $v$. Because Gold agents have $\delta_{g \to \cdot} = 0$, no propagation passes through a Gold agent. Therefore, all relevant paths are those that avoid Gold agents (except possibly $a$ itself if $a$ is Gold, in which case $v$ cannot be reached unless $v = a$). Let $\mathcal{P}_{a \to v}$ be the set of such paths. For a single path $p = (a = v_0, v_1, \dots, v_m = v)$, the probability that $v$ fails due to that path (assuming independence of failures along the path) is at most $\prod_{e \in p} \delta_e$. By the union bound over all paths, $\Pr[v \text{ fails}] \le \sum_{p \in \mathcal{P}_{a \to v}} \prod_{e \in p} \delta_e$. Since probabilities cannot exceed 1, we take the minimum with 1.

Summing over all $v \neq a$ gives the claimed bound. ∎

