A.9 Proof of Theorem 10.1 (Trust‑Weighted Compositional Correctness)

Theorem 10.1 (Trust‑Weighted Compositional Correctness).
Under the acyclic ordering, if for every agent $a$ the contract $\langle A_a \rangle\; a\; \langle G_a \rangle$ holds, and Gold agents implement the refusal primitive with rate limiting as described, then the composition satisfies $\bigwedge_a G_a$.

Proof.
We prove by induction on the topological order of the dependency graph.

Base case: Agents with no incoming dependencies (sources). For such an agent $a$, $A_a$ is an assumption about the environment. Since there are no other agents providing inputs, the environment is simply the physical world. By construction, the environment satisfies $A_a$ (we assume the environment is well‑behaved). The contract $\langle A_a \rangle\; a\; \langle G_a \rangle$ then guarantees that $a$ satisfies $G_a$.

Inductive step: Assume all agents $b$ that appear before $a$ in the topological order satisfy $G_b$. Consider agent $a$. Its assumption $A_a$ refers only to agents that provide inputs to $a$; these are strictly lower in the order (by acyclicity). By the induction hypothesis, those agents satisfy their $G_b$. In particular, they are compliant with their certification levels.

Now, the refusal filter on $a$ ensures that any input that would violate $A_a$ (either because it comes from an untrusted source that fails $\psi_{\text{safe}}$, or because it would exceed the per‑sender rate budget) is dropped. Hence the actual inputs that $a$ receives satisfy $A_a$. The rate‑limiting part guarantees that the condition $\text{rate}_{[t,t+w]}(p_{\text{in}}) \le R_a \cdot w$ holds globally, so $\mathsf{Fair}_{\text{res}}$ holds and $p_{\text{res}}$ occurs within $d$ steps after each $p_{\text{in}}$. Thus the environment $E$ formed by the composition of lower‑order agents together with the physical world satisfies $A_a$. By the contract $\langle A_a \rangle\; a\; \langle G_a \rangle$, the agent $a$ then satisfies $G_a$.

By induction, all agents satisfy their respective $G_a$. Therefore the entire composition satisfies $\bigwedge_a G_a$. ∎

