A.10 Proof of Theorem 12.1 (Soundness of Runtime Monitoring)

Theorem 12.1 (Soundness of Runtime Monitoring).
If the offline certification produces $\Pi^*$ such that $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) \models \varphi$, and the concrete system $T_a$ at runtime is the same system that was certified offline (i.e., the agent’s behavior model has not changed since certification), and the agent is monitor‑compatible with $\Pi^*$, then the runtime monitor’s verdicts are sound: a $\bot$ verdict indicates a real violation of $\varphi$, and a $\top$ verdict indicates that $\varphi$ holds for all future extensions that satisfy fairness.

Proof.
By Theorem 4.1, for any concrete run $\rho$ of $T_a$, its abstract trace $\overline{\rho} = \alpha(\rho)$ is a run of $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*)$. Because $\overline{T}_a(\Pi^*) \models \varphi$, we have $\overline{\rho} \models \varphi$. Moreover, because $\Pi^*$ contains predicates for all atomic propositions, $\rho \models \varphi$ iff $\overline{\rho} \models \varphi$. Hence $\rho \models \varphi$.

Now consider the runtime monitor. It observes the values of the predicates $\pi \in \Pi^*$ at each step, which by monitor‑compatibility correspond exactly to the truth values of the atomic propositions in $\rho$. Therefore the abstract trace $\overline{\rho}$ is exactly the trace of atomic propositions observed by the monitor.

Theorem 8.1 states that the monitor’s verdicts are correct with respect to the abstract trace: a $\bot$ verdict implies there exists a fairness‑satisfying extension violating $\varphi$, and a $\top$ verdict implies all fairness‑satisfying extensions satisfy $\varphi$. Since the abstract trace corresponds to the concrete trace, these implications carry over to the concrete system.

Thus the monitor’s verdicts are sound. ∎

