Appendix C: Additional Mathematical Background

C.1 Martingales and Azuma’s Inequality
A sequence of random variables $\{X_i\}_{i\ge 1}$ adapted to a filtration $\{\mathcal{F}_i\}$ is a martingale if $\mathbb{E}[|X_i|] < \infty$ and $\mathbb{E}[X_{i+1} \mid \mathcal{F}_i] = X_i$ almost surely. A martingale difference sequence $\{D_i\}$ satisfies $\mathbb{E}[D_i \mid \mathcal{F}_{i-1}] = 0$.

Azuma’s inequality: If $\{D_i\}$ is a martingale difference sequence with $|D_i| \le c_i$ almost surely, then for any $t > 0$,

\mathbb{P}\left(\sum_{i=1}^n D_i \ge t\right) \le \exp\left(-\frac{t^2}{2\sum_{i=1}^n c_i^2}\right).

In the thesis we use $c_i = 1$, giving the bound used in Theorem 6.1.

C.2 Craig Interpolation
Given two formulas $A$ and $B$ in a decidable theory (e.g., linear arithmetic) such that $A \implies B$ is valid, a Craig interpolant $I$ is a formula such that $A \implies I$, $I \implies B$, and all symbols in $I$ occur in both $A$ and $B$. In CEGAR, we obtain $A$ as the set of concrete states satisfying $\gamma(\bar{s}_i)$ and $B$ as the negation of the set of concrete states reachable via the transition; the interpolant becomes a new predicate that separates the two sets.

C.3 Kolmogorov’s Extension Theorem
For a sequence of random variables taking values in a Polish space (e.g., the set of atomic proposition valuations), Kolmogorov’s theorem guarantees the existence of a unique probability measure on the space of infinite sequences consistent with any finite‑dimensional distributions. This justifies Definition 6.1’s claim that the probability measure on infinite traces is well‑defined, even for non‑stationary policies.

